REVIEW OF LITERATURE

Overview of Rice Production in the Philippines
The Philippines remains one of the world's leading rice producers, ranking as the 8th largest globally, behind major rice-producing nations such as China, Indonesia, and India (DA Press Office, 2022). Rice farming in the country has a rich history spanning thousands of years and continues to serve as a cornerstone of Philippine agriculture. Since 2016, approximately five million hectares of land have been dedicated to rice cultivation, yielding about 20 million metric tons of unmilled rice in 2022 (Balita, 2024b). For 2023, the Department of Agriculture’s National Rice Program projects local palay production to reach 19.50 million metric tons, translating to 12.754 million metric tons of milled rice, despite the persistent challenges of rising costs for fuel, fertilizer, and other inputs (DA-AFID, 2022).
In terms of regional contributions, Luzon accounted for 45.5 percent of the country’s total agricultural and fisheries production at constant 2018 prices in 2023, as shown in Fig. 1. Mindanao followed with a substantial 36.7 percent share, driven by its fertile lands, favorable climate, and strategic position as a major agricultural hub (Philippine Statistics Authority, 2024). Known as the "food basket" of the Philippines, Mindanao plays a crucial role in the country’s rice production and serves as a key supplier of high-value crops such as rice, bananas, coconuts, and pineapples (Philippine Statistics Authority, 2020). The region's agricultural productivity continues to benefit from diverse cropping systems, farmer ingenuity, and the integration of advanced farming technologies, solidifying its role as a pillar of national food security and economic stability.
 
Fig. 1. Major Island Group Percent Share in the Total Value of Production in Agriculture and Fisheries at Constant 2018 Prices in 2023 lifted from (Philippine Statistics Authority, 2024).
In the Davao Region, agricultural productivity is exemplified by the average rice yields per hectare across its provinces. According to data presented in Fig. 2, Davao del Sur leads the region with the highest average yield at 4.84 metric tons per hectare, followed by Davao Oriental at 4.59 metric tons per hectare, Davao de Oro at 4.42 metric tons per hectare, and Davao del Norte at 4.39 metric tons per hectare. Davao Occidental, in contrast, lags significantly with an average yield of only 2.91 metric tons per hectare. These figures highlight significant disparities in agricultural efficiency and capacity within the region (Philippine Rice Research Institute, n.d.).
Davao del Sur, particularly the municipality of Hagonoy, is recognized as one of the leading rice-producing areas in Region XI. Hagonoy’s agricultural performance exceeds the provincial and regional averages, with average yields surpassing six metric tons per hectare compared to the provincial average of just over five metric tons and the regional average of around four metric tons. The municipality’s 1,436 farmers manage approximately 2,046 hectares of irrigated rice fields, contributing significantly to local rice production (Hondrade, 2007). 
  
Fig. 2. Average Yield per Hectare by Year 2023 in Davao Region by Province lifted from RiceLytics (Betran et al., n.d.).
Moreover, the municipality's fertile soil, which are adaptable to a variety of crops, further bolster its agricultural capacity. According to Hondrade (2007), about 10,000 hectares in Hagonoy are suitable for coconut, corn, sugarcane, and irrigated lowland rice. Fig. 3 provides a comparative perspective on rice productivity across the municipalities of Davao del Sur in 2023. Among the municipalities, Matan-ao recorded the highest average rice yield of 5.05 metric tons per hectare, followed by Kiblawan with 5.00 metric tons per hectare. These municipalities demonstrate superior rice productivity, likely due to optimized agronomic practices, advanced irrigation systems, and favorable agroecological conditions. Conversely, Sulop and Malalag are at the lower end of the spectrum, with yields of 4.62 and 4.55 metric tons per hectare, respectively. Hagonoy, with an average yield of 4.97 metric tons per hectare, stands as one of the better-performing municipalities in the province.
 
Fig. 3. Average Yield per Hectare by Year in Davao del Sur by Municipality lifted from RiceLytics (Betran et al., n.d.). Hagonoy being the fourth highest average yield among all municipalities with 4.97 MT/ha.
The yield performance of Hagonoy suggests the presence of effective agricultural practices, reliable irrigation infrastructure, and moderate resilience to challenges such as pests, diseases, and adverse weather conditions. However, its slight yield gap compared to the leading municipalities such as Matan-ao and Kiblawan indicates areas for improvement. These differences could be attributed to variations in irrigation efficiency, fertilizer application timing and methods, selection of rice varieties, and pest and disease management practices. By addressing these gaps, Hagonoy has the potential to enhance its agricultural performance further.
To strengthen rice production and resilience in Hagonoy, research institutions across the Philippines have been actively developing new rice varieties and refining cultivation techniques. These advancements aim to improve crop maturation processes and mitigate the impacts of climate change on agriculture. The integration of modern farming practices, alongside the utilization of diversified rice varieties, has been instrumental in boosting rice yields nationally (Balita, 2024b; DA Press Office, 2022). These innovations, when tailored to the specific needs of Hagonoy and supported by localized training programs, could drive further improvements in rice productivity.
Hagonoy exemplifies significant potential as a high-performing rice-producing municipality in Davao del Sur. With targeted interventions and continued adoption of science-based agricultural practices, it can further solidify its contribution to regional and national food security. Achieving this, however, requires a clear understanding of the biological and agronomic foundations that govern rice yield.
Plant Morphology and Varietal Influences on Rice Yield
A deeper appreciation of the rice plant’s biology and the agronomic factors influencing yield is essential for optimizing productivity in high-performing areas such as Hagonoy. Rice yield is fundamentally shaped by the plant’s morphological characteristics, the classification of varieties, and the processes of grain development. Insights into these aspects provide the scientific basis for identifying yield determinants and designing effective, targeted interventions that respond to the needs of local farmers.
The rice plant
Rice, belonging to the family Gramineae and the genus Oryza, is a staple crop with significant global importance. Of the approximately 20 species within the genus, only Oryza sativa L. ("Asian rice") and Oryza glaberrima Steud. ("African rice") are commonly cultivated, with Oryza sativa being the predominant species worldwide (RiceHub, n.d.). Within Oryza sativa, three main subspecies are recognized: indica, javanica, and japonica, each adapted to different geographic and climatic conditions (Heinrichs, n.d.).
Indica varieties thrive in tropical and subtropical regions, making them a staple in South and Southeast Asia and southern China. Javanica varieties, including bulu (awned) and gundil (awnless) types, are notable for long panicles and bold grains, and are primarily grown in Indonesia. Japonica varieties, with their short, round grains, are suited to temperate climates and widely cultivated in Japan, China, and Korea. The adaptability of these varieties to specific conditions influences their distribution and productivity; for example, japonica rice is grown in northern California for its tolerance to lower night temperatures, whereas indica dominates southern U.S. regions (Heinrichs, n.d.).
Palay. In the Filipino context, palay refers to rice at any stage prior to husking (Merriam-Webster, n.d.). It is an annual warm-season grass that typically reaches heights of 1 to 1.8 meters, depending on variety and soil fertility. Its long, slender leaves, which are up to 100 centimeters in length are rough-textured with fine notches and prickles. The plant’s fibrous root system, consisting of seminal and nodal roots with lateral branches, is essential for water and nutrient absorption, paralleling other cereal crops.
 
Fig. 4. The anatomy of Rice plant lifted from bioRender.com by Eunice Huang (n.d.).
The reproductive structure of the rice plant is the panicle, a branched inflorescence that can grow up to 30 centimeters long. As grains mature, the panicle droops, bearing 80 to 120 grains on average, though this number varies with variety, environment, and crop management. Each grain is enclosed within a protective husk (rice hull), forming the pericarp of the ripened ovary and typically exhibiting an oblong or ovoid shape. The edible portion, or bigas in Filipino, is about 12 millimeters long and 3 millimeters thick. Grain and husk color changes as the grain ripens, with varieties displaying white, brown, or black grains (Chang and Bardenas, 1965; Matic Hub, 2021; RiceHub, n.d.).
Understanding the anatomy of the rice plant is crucial for yield optimization. The roots secure the plant and facilitate nutrient uptake; stems transport water and nutrients; leaves drive photosynthesis; and tillers produce shoots that form additional panicles. Each panicle’s grain yield is determined by genetic, environmental, and management factors. A closer look in Fig. 4 at the rice grain reveals its by-products: the protective husk, nutrient-rich bran, starchy white rice, and the germ, all of which play roles in agricultural productivity and food value (International Rice Research Institute, n.d.). 
Beyond these biological foundations, the ways in which farmers cultivate and manage rice have a deep impact on overall productivity.
Rice Farming Practices in the Philippines
The evolution of rice farming practices in the Philippines highlights a continuous effort to improve productivity, sustainability, and adaptability to changing agricultural needs. Historical developments in rice production are closely tied to the introduction of new rice varieties, which can be categorized into three major eras: Pre-Green Revolution, Green Revolution, and Post-Green Revolution. During the pre-Green Revolution, traditional rice varieties dominated, with farmers typically planting only once a year. The Green Revolution (1966–1988) introduced high-yielding varieties that supported two growing seasons annually, significantly boosting productivity. The post-Green Revolution period (1989 to present) focuses on enhancing both yield and sustainability through advanced practices and technologies (Bautista and Javier, 2005; Vicente et al., 2023). The Bureau of Agriculture and Fisheries Standards (BAFS) (2019) developed the Philippine National Standard (PNS) Code of Good Agricultural Practices (GAP) for Rice for setting consolidated safety and quality standards covering the production, harvesting and on farm post-harvest handling and storage of rice.
Good agricultural practices (GAP)
According to the Agricultural Training Institute (2022), Good Agricultural Practices (GAP) refer to farm-level approaches designed to minimize the risk of contamination throughout both on-farm production and postproduction processes. GAP recommendations emphasize environmental protection, food safety, worker health and welfare, and product quality. These practices are guided by principles, regulations, and technical recommendations that apply to primary production, processing, and food transport. The guidelines established and agreed upon by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), which the Philippines as one of its ten member countries, serve as a bridge between traditional farming methods and the modern market, aligning agricultural production with the standards and expectations of various stakeholders, including consumers.
For rice production, GAP highlights several key areas for inspection: the farm’s location and environment, structural and facility maintenance, farming practices, worker health and safety, and overall management. Effective implementation of GAP requires proper farm management, which includes constructing suitable farm structures such as waste disposal facilities and dedicated storage areas for harvested produce and equipment, as well as clearly marked and labeled field plots. Sustainable practices, such as efficient soil and water management, responsible use of pesticides and fertilizers, and integrated pest and disease control, are essential for compliance. Furthermore, harvesting, packaging, and storage must meet strict quality standards. Consideration of a farm’s history including prior land use and neighboring activities, along with comprehensive record-keeping of inputs, practices, produce, sales, and training, ensures that farms meet GAP requirements and secure certification (Agricultural Training Institute, 2022; Palizada, 2016).
Building on these GAP principles, specific recommendations for enhancing Philippine rice productivity have been identified through research initiatives. PhilRice-IRRI study recommends the use of hybrid varieties, optimal use of fertilizers, training of more farmers on rice technologies, and educating future farmers as some of the ways to boost rice productivity in the country (Pasiona, 2015). Bordey et al. (2015) further highlights that competitiveness rests on the ability of a farmer to produce palay at the same or superior quality and at a lower cost than local or international competitors. They emphasize the promotion of hybrid rice technology coupled with appropriate crop management, intensified use of labor-saving technologies such as combines harvesters and direct seeding, continued irrigation programs, and improved milling efficiency. The study further stresses the need to invest in state-of-the-art rice research and development (R&D) initiatives to create next-generation technologies for future yield growth.

 
Fig. 5. Status of PhilGAP Implementation as of 2016 lifted from Palizada (2016). Region II recorded the highest number of certified farmers, followed by Region III, with Regions I and XI tied as the third highest in terms of certifications.
Despite government efforts through the Department of Agriculture to strengthen and intensify the PhilGAP program, implementation across Philippine regions remains uneven. Fig. 5 illustrates these disparities: Region II leads with 49 certified farms, followed by Region III with 12, while Region XI lags with only 4 certified farms (Palizada, 2016). 
This uneven adoption highlights substantial challenges in achieving widespread certification and reflects underlying barriers to effective implementation of GAP in certain areas. Addressing these challenges, through increased awareness, robust support systems, and infrastructure investments, this can improve certification rates. Furthermore, these requires increased awareness and support among farmers. Given its agricultural potential, Region XI could enhance its performance and contribute more substantially to food safety, produce quality, and market competitiveness. 
Digital rice production knowledge platforms
The International Rice Research Institute (IRRI) developed the Rice Knowledge Bank (RKB). It is a digital extension service offering practical solutions tailored to small-scale farmers. The RKB integrates cutting-edge agricultural techniques, best practices, and research findings to help farmers optimize their processes. Building on this foundation, the Philippine Rice Research Institute (PhilRice) created the localized Pinoy Rice Knowledge Bank (PRKB), which adapts the RKB framework to the specific needs of Filipino farmers. The PRKB provides country-specific, up-to-date information on rice and rice-based cropping systems, ensuring relevance to the local context (International Rice Research Institute, n.d.).
In Fig. 6, the RKB outlines the three essential stages of rice production: pre-planting, growth, and post-harvest. Pre-planting activities include selecting the right variety, preparing cropping calendars, and field preparation, which are foundational for a successful rice crop. During the growth stage, farmers focus on managing water, fertilizers, pests, and weeds to ensure healthy crop development. Finally, post-harvest processes such as drying, storage, and milling are critical for maintaining the quality and marketability of the rice harvest  (“Step-by-step production - IRRI Rice Knowledge Bank,” n.d.).
 
Fig. 6. Step-by-step production of Rice lifted from IRRI Rice Knowledge Bank (n.d.). 
 
Fig. 7. The Pinoy Rice Knowledge Bank website lifted from Philippine Rice Research Institute (n.d.).
Complementing the global perspective provided by the RKB, the PRKB, as shown in Fig. 7, serves as a rich repository of localized information designed specifically for Filipino farmers. It offers extensive resources on rice farming in the Philippines, including downloadable materials such as videos and PowerPoint presentations. These materials focus on yield-enhancing and cost-reducing technologies, empowering farmers to optimize their practices in alignment with the unique challenges and opportunities in the Philippine agricultural landscape (Philippine Rice Research Institute, n.d.).
Local rice production practices. Rice farming in Barangay Balutakay, Hagonoy, Davao del Sur (2014) reflects these broader developments in a community-specific context. According to their Barangay Development Plan, rice is grown biannually in two primary seasons: the “panuig” (wet season) and the “pangulilang” (dry season). 
Illustrated in Fig. 8, the dry season begins with land preparation in December (in color blue), followed by planting in January (green color), maintenance through March and April (yellow color), and harvesting in April (orange color). 

 
Fig. 8. Cropping Pattern of Rice and Corn in Barangay Balukatay, Hagonoy lifted from the Barangay Balutakay, Hagonoy, Davao del Sur (2014).
During the wet season, land preparation starts in June, with planting completed by July, maintenance carried out through August and September, and harvesting in October. In the transition months of May and November, farmers commonly plant alternative crops such as watermelon or mung beans. Crop yield is closely linked to the timely availability and application of inputs, which can be impacted by rising costs. 
The evolution of rice farming practices in the Philippines, from traditional methods to the adoption of Good Agricultural Practices (GAP) and digital extension platforms like the Rice Knowledge Bank, shows an ongoing commitment to increasing productivity, ensuring sustainability, and addressing the diverse challenges faced by local farmers. However, as shown by regional disparities in GAP certification and the influence of local cropping patterns, the effectiveness of these initiatives relies on the timely and efficient management of fundamental production inputs. These practices are closely connected to the key factors that determine rice yield, such as the selection and use of high-quality seeds, proper fertilizer and pesticide management, efficient land preparation, and adaptation to environmental and economic conditions. The next section examines these critical factors, drawing on both local and international research to better understand their roles in shaping rice yield outcomes in the Philippines.
Key Factors of Rice Production
The success of rice production is heavily influenced by the quantity and quality of key inputs in farming. Influenced by a complex interplay of agronomic, environmental, economic, and technological factors, these inputs can play critical roles in determining yield essential for improving rice farming outcomes in the Philippines, as highlighted in several studies. 
Ginting and Andari (2021) conducted research in Tanah Miring District, Merauke Regency, Indonesia, showing that seeds, fertilizers, pesticides, and labor collectively have a significant impact on rice production, as indicated by an F-test value of 0.000. However, when analyzed individually, only seeds and pesticides had a statistically significant effect, while fertilizers and labor showed no significant influence. This suggests that optimizing seed quality and pesticide use is crucial for improving yields, whereas the effects of fertilizers and labor may depend on factors like soil conditions and farming practices.
Koirala et al. (2013) examined the technical efficiency of rice farmers in the Philippines using a stochastic frontier production model. Their findings emphasized that fertilizer costs and land area were significant determinants of production. A 1% increase in land area resulted in a 0.48% increase in output, highlighting the critical role of expanding the acreage in enhancing productivity. Other factors such as fuel costs, planting season, and land rent also significantly affected production and efficiency. In contrast, herbicide use had no direct effect on productivity, as it primarily functions to prevent damage rather than boost yield.
Dait (2023) analyzed the effects of climate and economic variables on rice production across six major rice-producing regions in the Philippines. The study found that land area and urea application significantly increased rice production in irrigated areas, while rainfall and temperature negatively impacted yields. In rainfed areas, both land area and fertilizer use were positively associated with production, although adverse effects of rainfall were noted. The findings underscored the importance of long-term strategies to expand land use, improve irrigation systems, and adopt climate-resilient farming practices to sustain production levels.
David (2023) highlighted the indirect but significant effects of environmental factors such as rainfall, wind speed, and atmospheric pressure on rice yields in the Pampanga River Basin. These variables influence the growth and development of rice crops, emphasizing the need to consider environmental conditions when managing agronomic inputs.
Ashari et al. (2024) pointed out that yield losses occur across multiple stages of the supply chain, including harvesting, drying, storage, and milling. Factors like crop variety, harvest timing, and the use of agricultural tools significantly influence yield losses. The study recommended adopting modern agricultural technologies and good agricultural practices (GAP) to minimize these losses.
The table above presents a summary of key inputs identified in the literature, along with their corresponding references. As shown in Table 1, these have been recognized across multiple studies as critical determinants of rice yield. Optimizing the management of key inputs such as seeds, fertilizers, pesticides, and land area is essential for achieving higher rice yields in the Philippines. 
Table 1. Summary of related studies on key factors of rice production.
Factor	Category	References
Seeds	Agronomic	Ginting & Andari (2021)
Fertilizer	Agronomic, Economic	Ginting & Andari (2021); Koirala et al. (2013); Dait (2023)
Pesticide	Agronomic	Ginting & Andari (2021)
