The selection of high-quality seeds and the use of effective pest control methods can directly increase crop productivity, as highlighted in studies on technology adoption and crop management practices (Mariano et al., 2012; Matala et al., 2011). Fertilizer use and land allocation require careful consideration of local agronomic and economic factors to maximize benefits (Matala et al., 2011). Additionally, minimizing inefficiencies in the supply chain and adopting climate-resilient farming practices can enhance both productivity and sustainability (Dait, 2023; Stuecker et al., 2018). 
While environmental factors such as rainfall and temperature are included due to their significant impact on rice yield, this review emphasizes factor that farmers can directly manage and optimize. This focus can allow for the development of practical recommendations that can be adopted at the farm level to improve productivity. By focusing on these actionable factors, practical recommendations can be developed to empower farmers in improving productivity at the ground level. Considering rapid advancements in agricultural practices, farmers now have access to emerging tools and strategies that further support their decision-making and input management.
Digital Technologies and Tools in Rice Farming
The integration of information and communication technologies (ICT) into rice farming represents a transformative shift toward more precise and data-driven agricultural practices. Digital innovations such as mobile applications and smart farming solutions are not only modernizing traditional methods but also equipping farmers with real-time information, advanced analytics, and practical tools to address longstanding challenges and realize their yield potential. As highlighted by Tallada (2019), ICT holds immense promise for revolutionizing local rice production by boosting efficiency, lowering costs, and increasing yields through the adoption of precision agriculture techniques.
Building on these developments, Gabrillo and Torres (2022) investigated the practical impact of rice-specific ICT tools on both farmers and agricultural extension workers (AEWs). Their findings indicate that the adoption of ICT platforms enables farmers to better manage nutrients, forge stronger connections with buyers, and achieve higher productivity. For AEWs, these technologies streamline advisory tasks, enhance the delivery of services, and foster greater professional empowerment. Nonetheless, the widespread adoption of ICT in agriculture is still hindered by challenges such as high mobile data costs and unreliable network signals, which remain significant barriers, particularly in rural areas.
 
Fig. 9. Binhing Palay user interface lifted from the study of Tallada (2019). This provides agronomic and grain quality characteristics of different rice varieties in the Philippines.
Existing mobile applications in rice farming
Angchay et al. (2024) conducted a qualitative study involving fourteen rice farmers in Davao del Sur. The aim was to thoroughly examine and document their experiences with using various agricultural applications on their smartphones for rice cultivation. They explored how digital interventions are shaping the practices and livelihoods of smallholder rice farmers in the region. The findings of the study highlight the transformative potential of these agri-apps, revealing that most participants experienced notable increases in both income and farming efficiency after integrating mobile technology into their agricultural routines. This positive impact was particularly distinct among those farmers who had participated in formal training sessions on the use of mobile applications, suggesting that digital literacy and capacity-building are essential components for successful technological adoption in agriculture.
Binhing Palay app. The Binhing Palay app, as shown in Fig. 9, provides agronomic and grain quality characteristics of over 200 rice varieties in the Philippines (Tallada, 2019). Developed by the Philippine Rice Research Institute (2021), this app serves as a guide for selecting rice varieties to plant before the season begins. It offers detailed information about yield, maturity, height, pest resistance, and other essential traits for each rice variety. Its search functionality and offline accessibility make it a reliable tool for decision-making (Softonic, n.d.).
eDamuhan app. The eDamuhan app, shown in Fig. 10, employs artificial intelligence for weed identification and control management. Farmers take photos of weeds using their phone’s camera, which are then analyzed by a central server using TensorFlow technology to identify the species. The app provides detailed information on the identified weed and its proper management techniques (Tallada, 2019). Angchay et al. (2024) noted that farmers described this app as a practical tool for managing weeds effectively, addressing a critical aspect of rice farming.
 
Fig. 10. eDamuhan app user interface lifted from Tallada (2019). An artificial intelligence-based application for weed identification and control management.

 
Fig. 11. The Minus-One Element Technique (MOET)-app user interface lifted from Tallada (2019). An android-based app that computes for fertilizer recommendations and yield estimates based on the pot-based fertilizer trial to identify significant nutrient elements lacking in the soil.
Minus-One Element Technique (MOET) app. Illustrated in Fig. 11, the MOET app assists farmers in assessing soil nutrient deficiencies through a pot-based fertilizer trial. Using composite soil samples, the app calculates fertilizer recommendations and yield estimates based on the biomass yield of potted rice plants. This removes much of the guesswork in fertility management, allowing farmers to make informed decisions about nutrient application (Tallada, 2019). Younger farmers, enthusiastic about integrating smartphone technologies into farming, have shown significant interest in this app.
PhilRice Leaf Color Computing Application. Based on a four-striped handheld tool known as the Leaf Color Chart (LCC), the PhilRice Leaf Color Computing Application (PhilRice LCC App) is designed to evaluate the nitrogen status of rice plants. (Philippine Rice Research Institute, 2021b). Shown in Fig. 12, it is an innovative tool designed to enhance precision agriculture by providing real-time fertilizer recommendations for rice farming. Using a smartphone's front camera, the app enables farmers to capture images of rice leaves, which are analyzed to assess nitrogen levels and determine precise fertilizer needs. The app provides recommendations for fertilizer application at critical growth stages, including the basal and panicle initiation stages, optimizing nutrient management and improving crop yield.
Additionally, the LCC App features a simple record-keeping system that allows farmers to document their fertilizer applications systematically. It also includes a farm profile feature to help track farm status, enabling informed and efficient farm management. Notably, the app supports all rice varieties registered under the National Seed Quality Control Services (NSQCS) as well as privately produced varieties, ensuring broad applicability across different farming contexts. These functionalities make the LCC App a valuable resource for promoting sustainable and efficient rice farming practices.
Table 2 summarizes the main features of each app as reported in the literature. Each application addresses needs. For example, eDamuhan specializes in weed identification, PhilRice LCC focuses on LCC-based nutrient management, and MOET app provides region-specific nutrient recommendations.
     
