However, gaps remain, such as limited integration of variety selection, pest management, and local language support across the board. GabayPalay app is projected to address several of these gaps, while still having room for future enhancement in features like LCC and weed management.
In addition to these applications, farmers also use Accuweather app, SpidTech app, and Rice Doctor app (Angchay et al., 2024), all of which are readily available for download on the Google Play Store and are actively promoted on social media platforms. While the effectiveness of these applications remains under evaluation, they have sparked interest among farmers, particularly the younger generation, who are more inclined to adopt digital tools in their agricultural practices (Tallada, 2019).
Motivation for and impact of adopting rice farming applications
The growing interest and willingness to explore of these digital applications can be attributed in large part to government-led training programs, particularly the Digital Farmers Program 103 for Rice (DFP 103 for Rice) conducted by the Department of Agriculture’s Agricultural Training Institute. Angchay et al. (2024) found that most rice farmers in Davao del Sur only began using mobile agricultural tools after attending such training, which emphasized hands-on practice and guidance in utilizing smartphone technology for agriculture. Only a few had prior exposure to these technologies, while the majority credited their newfound confidence and skills to formal capacity-building initiatives.
With this increased digital literacy and institutional support, farmers were able to incorporate smartphone-based farming applications more effectively into their daily routines. The impact of these digital platforms on rice production has been substantial. Farmers reported that the integration of digital tools into their routines led to greater efficiency and productivity (Angchay et al., 2024). Previously, they relied on traditional and often imprecise methods for weather forecasting, pest management, and crop selection, such as observing the sky or interpreting animal behavior. With the introduction of resources like Accuweather, Binhing Palay, and other mobile services, farmers can now make data-driven decisions, enabling more precise timing of agricultural operations, better selection of rice varieties, and optimized use of inputs such as fertilizers and pesticides (Angchay et al., 2024; Tallada, 2019).
Many participants noted that agri-apps not only simplified their work but also contributed to increased income. Digital recommendations for input management and weather forecasts helped reduce wasted resources and improved yields. Furthermore, the ability to access accurate information independently reduced their reliance on agricultural extension workers for routine problems, allowing for quicker and more autonomous decision-making (Angchay et al., 2024). Overall, the experience of Davao del Sur rice farmers demonstrates that with proper support and training, digital agriculture tools can bring about meaningful improvements in both farm efficiency and livelihoods.
Challenges in utilizing mobile technologies for rice production
While the benefits of digital tools in rice production are evident, several challenges continue to hinder their widespread and effective adoption. Limited digital literacy remains a major barrier, especially among older farmers and those with little formal education. Many first-time users have trouble navigating smartphone interfaces and understanding how to properly utilize various features of agricultural applications. This lack of familiarity often leads to hesitation or lack of confidence in using new technologies for farm management (Angchay et al., 2024; Gabrillo and Torres, 2022).
Another persistent obstacle is the issue of connectivity. In many rural areas, slow or unreliable internet access restricts farmers’ ability to fully utilize mobile applications that require regular updates or real-time data retrieval. This technical limitation not only affects the experience of using these platforms but also discourages sustained engagement, especially when farmers encounter repeated disruptions or delays (Gabrillo and Torres, 2022).
Additionally, some farmers expressed concerns regarding the accuracy and relevance of information provided by certain applications. Occasional mismatches between local conditions and app recommendations can lead to frustration and uncertainty. There is also a perceived gap in personalized technical support, with some users finding it challenging to access timely assistance when encountering problems or needing clarification.
Despite these barriers, the resilience and adaptability of rice farmers remain evident. Many continue to seek out opportunities for further training and peer learning, recognizing the long-term advantages of digital technologies in agriculture. Ongoing efforts to improve digital infrastructure and expand farmer education are essential to overcome these challenges and enable more inclusive and effective adoption of mobile technologies in rice production (Angchay et al., 2024; Gabrillo and Torres, 2022).
Yield Prediction Models in Rice Production Systems
Despite the promising adoption of mobile applications among rice farmers in Davao del Sur, challenges regarding the accuracy and relevance of information provided by certain applications continue to persist. Angchay et al. (2024) noted that some farmers expressed concerns about occasional mismatches between local conditions and app recommendations, which can lead to frustration and uncertainty in decision-making. Additionally, Gabrillo and Torres (2022) identified that while ICT platforms enable farmers to better manage nutrients and achieve higher productivity, widespread adoption is still hindered by technical limitations and reliability issues. To address these accuracy concerns and provide more precise agricultural recommendations that account for the complex interactions between multiple agronomic factors, mathematical modeling approaches have gained prominence in agricultural research.
Mathematical modeling has emerged as a critical tool in modern agriculture for predicting crop yields and optimizing farming decisions. Jagathesan (2020) highlights that the application of mathematical models in agriculture incorporates analytical, simulation, and empirical methods through five key stages: formulation, solution, interpretation, and validation. These models combine equations, charts, and formulas based on theory and literature to provide precision and strategic solutions to agricultural problems.
Several machine learning approaches have been employed for crop yield prediction, each with distinct characteristics and limitations. The selection of an appropriate model depends on factors such as data complexity, interpretability requirements, and prediction accuracy needs. The studies of David (2023) and Jiya et al. (2023) provide comprehensive evaluations of various predictive models for rice yield estimation.
Linear Regression model 
Linear Regression (LiR) models describe the relationship between a dependent variable, y, and one or more independent variables, X. The dependent variable is also called the response variable, while independent variables are known as predictors, covariates (if continuous), or factors (if categorical). The matrix X, which contains predictor observations, is typically called the design matrix. (The MathWorks Inc., n.d.). 
The study of David (2023) modeled the relationship between rice crop yield (RCY) and explanatory variables using a linear equation. The response variable is rice yield (in kilograms per hectare), while the explanatory variables include factors such as material inputs. The mathematical representation of the linear regression model is expressed in equation [1]:
Y=α+β_1 "X" _1+β_2 "X" _2+β_3 "X" _3+⋯+β_n "X" _n	[1]

While LiR provides interpretable results and computational efficiency, its linear assumption limits its ability to capture complex, non-linear relationships common in agricultural systems. As shown in Table 3, David (2023) demonstrated that LiR exhibited the poorest performance among the three models tested, with the highest training MSE (0.190) and lowest R² values (0.551 for training, 0.572 for testing). These results indicate significant limitations in LiR's ability to handle the complexities of rice yield prediction.
Artificial Neural Network model
Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) are computational models inspired by the human brain's neural architecture, designed to recognize patterns and solve complex problems through learning from data. Mathematically, an ANN consists of interconnected layers of nodes (neurons), where each connection has an associated weight. The output of each neuron is determined by applying an activation function to the weighted sum of its inputs. This architecture allows ANNs to approximate non-linear relationships effectively (GeeksforGeeks, 2024a; Gill, 2024).
The study of David (2023) utilized a multilayer perceptron architecture with an input layer of 15 features, two hidden layers consisting of 20 and 10 neurons respectively, and an output layer predicting rice crop yield (RCY). The study incrementally increased the number of neurons in the hidden layers and evaluated performance using Mean Squared Error (MSE), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), and the Coefficient of Determination (R²). 
Table 3. Training and testing performance of three models from the study of David (2023).
Model	Training Performance Score	Testing Performance Score
	MSE	RMSE	MAE	R2	MSE	RMSE	MAE	R2
ANN	0.024	0.155	0.104	0.943	0.287	0.536	0.426	0.365
LiR	0.190	0.436	0.350	0.551	0.194	0.440	0.349	0.572
RF	0.032	0.179	0.133	0.924	0.159	0.399	0.295	0.647

This process identified optimal neuron combinations in the hidden layers for best data fitting. After determining these combinations, hyperparameter tuning was conducted to select an appropriate activation function and solver, specifically the Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU) activation function and Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) solver.
Despite ANN's ability to model complex non-linear relationships, the study revealed significant challenges with overfitting. As shown in Table 3, while the ANN model achieved the best training performance with the lowest MSE (0.024), RMSE (0.155), and MAE (0.104) scores, as well as the highest R² score (0.943), it exhibited a dramatic decline in testing performance with an R² value dropping to 0.365. This substantial performance gap indicates that ANNs require larger datasets and careful hyperparameter tuning to avoid memorizing training patterns rather than learning generalizable relationships.
Other predictive models
Additional models have been evaluated for rice yield prediction, each with specific characteristics and performance levels. Jiya et al. (2023) evaluated Random Trees (RT), Logistic Regression (LoR), and Naïve Bayes (NB) alongside other models. As shown in Table 4, RT demonstrated exceptional performance with perfect scores for MAE (0), RMSE (0), RAE (0%), and RRSE (0%), achieving 100% accuracy. However, such perfect performance may indicate potential overfitting to the specific dataset.
Naïve Bayes ranked third among the models, achieving an MAE of 0.082, RMSE of 0.21, and 91.6% accuracy. Logistic Regression and ANN both showed comparatively lower accuracy at 75%, with LoR achieving an MAE of 0.15 and RMSE of 0.3, while ANN recorded an MAE of 0.16 and RMSE of 0.35.
